<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ INTRODUCTION ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="introduction">
  <div class="section-label">Section I</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Who Are <em>the Rors?</em></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">
    The Rors are a predominantly agrarian and historically martial community concentrated in the plains of Haryana, southern Punjab, and western Uttar Pradesh. Though modest in population, they occupy a distinctive niche in North Indian social history — claiming ancient lineage, maintaining rigid endogamy, and asserting Kshatriya status in Hindu social hierarchy.
  </p>

  <div class="stat-chips">
    <div class="stat-chip"><strong>~150,000–200,000</strong> Estimated population (early 21st century)</div>
    <div class="stat-chip"><strong>3 States</strong> Primary: Haryana, Punjab, W. UP</div>
    <div class="stat-chip"><strong>Haryanvi</strong> Primary language spoken</div>
    <div class="stat-chip"><strong>Endogamous</strong> Strict in-community marriage tradition</div>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <h3>Primary Regions of Settlement</h3>
      <p>The Rors are found most densely in the districts of Rohtak, Sonipat, Hisar, Jhajjar, Panipat, and Karnal in Haryana. Their presence extends into Ambala and Kurukshetra districts, and into the Muzaffarnagar and Saharanpur areas of western Uttar Pradesh. Some communities exist in Punjab's eastern districts.</p>
      <p>Their heartland roughly corresponds to the ancient Kurukshetra region — the site of the Mahabharata war — which has given rise to various Ror claims of antiquity and Kshatriya descent, though these connections remain in the domain of oral tradition rather than verified history.</p>

      <h3>Social Identity &amp; Occupation</h3>
      <p>Historically, the Rors have been primarily agriculturalists — owning land and cultivating it. Unlike service castes, they did not traditionally perform artisanal or service roles in the jajmani system. Their self-identification places them alongside Jats, Rajputs, and Gujjars as landed, martial peasant proprietors.</p>
      <p>Colonial administrators classified them variably — sometimes as a "good agricultural tribe," other times as a caste with martial characteristics. The community did not achieve the formal "martial race" designation that Jats and Rajputs received under the British, though they served in local armies and militias.</p>
    </div>
    <div>
      <h3>Common Gotras &amp; Clans</h3>
      <p>The Rors are divided into clan groups called <em>gotras</em>, each tracing patrilineal descent from a common ancestor. Marriage within the same gotra is traditionally prohibited. Key gotras include:</p>

      <div class="tag-cloud">
        <span class="tag">Bhatiwal</span>
        <span class="tag">Dahiya</span>
        <span class="tag">Saini</span>
        <span class="tag">Khinda</span>
        <span class="tag">Kalkal</span>
        <span class="tag">Khokhar</span>
        <span class="tag">Mor</span>
        <span class="tag">Gahlawat</span>
        <span class="tag">Kaswan</span>
        <span class="tag">Dhull</span>
        <span class="tag">Sangwan</span>
        <span class="tag">Maan</span>
        <span class="tag">Sehrawat</span>
        <span class="tag">Phogat</span>
        <span class="tag">Dalal</span>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-note">
        <div class="callout-title">Note on Gotra Overlap</div>
        <p>Many of these gotras are shared with Jats and Rajputs of the same region. This overlap is historically significant and has fueled both claims of kinship and debates about the distinct identity of the Ror community.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>Language &amp; Cultural Affiliation</h3>
      <p>Rors speak Haryanvi — a dialect of Western Hindi — as their primary language. Their cultural practices, festivals, dress, and folk traditions align closely with broader Haryanvi culture, overlapping significantly with neighboring Jat communities in food, music, and agricultural ritual.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ ORIGINS ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="origins">
  <div class="section-label">Section II</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Historical <em>Origins</em></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">
    The question of Ror origins is genuinely contested — among historians, anthropologists, geneticists, and the community itself. No single origin theory commands consensus. Below, we separate what evidence says from what tradition claims.
  </p>

  <div class="epistemic-legend">
    <span>Legend:</span>
    <span class="epistemic-badge badge-verified">Verified</span> Supported by archaeological, epigraphic, or documentary evidence
    <span class="epistemic-badge badge-tradition">Oral Tradition</span> Community memory, genealogies
    <span class="epistemic-badge badge-hypothesis">Hypothesis</span> Academic conjecture, plausible but unproven
    <span class="epistemic-badge badge-colonial">Colonial Account</span> British-era ethnography, treat critically
    <span class="epistemic-badge badge-disputed">Disputed</span> Actively contested or likely inaccurate
  </div>

  <div class="two-col">
    <div>
      <h3>The Name "Ror": Etymological Debate</h3>
      <p>The etymology of the word "Ror" is itself contested. Three main proposals exist:</p>
      <p><strong>1. Sanskrit <em>Roru</em> / <em>Ruru</em>:</strong> <span class="epistemic-badge badge-hypothesis">Hypothesis</span> Some scholars propose a Sanskrit origin, possibly from a tribal or clan name in early Hindu texts. This connection is speculative and not backed by definitive textual evidence.</p>
      <p><strong>2. Connection to <em>Ror Kingdom</em> (Sindh):</strong> <span class="epistemic-badge badge-hypothesis">Hypothesis</span> Medieval Sindh was home to a Hindu kingdom called the Ror dynasty (approximately 2nd century BCE – 7th century CE), which ruled parts of what is now Sindh and lower Punjab. Some historians and the Ror community itself claim descent from this Sindhi kingdom's ruling lineage. This connection has geographic plausibility but lacks direct genealogical documentation.</p>
      <p><strong>3. Indo-Scythian / Saka Connection:</strong> <span class="epistemic-badge badge-disputed">Disputed</span> Colonial-era ethnographers suggested some North Indian agrarian castes, including Rors, might descend from the Indo-Scythians (Sakas) who entered the subcontinent around 1st–2nd century BCE. This theory was popular in the 19th century but is now considered oversimplified. Modern historians note that "Saka" was likely a political-administrative category, not an ethnic label, and wholesale identification of any caste with "Scythian" settlers is rejected by mainstream anthropology.</p>

      <h3>The Ror Kingdom of Sindh</h3>
      <p>The historical Ror dynasty is among the better-documented claims. Arab geographers and the medieval chronicle <em>Chach Nama</em> (the Arab conquest of Sindh, 711–713 CE) describe the pre-Islamic rulers of Sindh as the Ror dynasty, defeated by Muhammad bin Qasim.</p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"The Ror dynasty ruled over the Indus delta and its hinterland before the Arab invasion. After conquest, some of the ruling lineages likely dispersed northward into Punjab and Haryana."</p>
        <cite>Paraphrase of accounts in Chach Nama and subsequent regional histories — primary source, 8th century CE</cite>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-title">Historical Note</div>
        <p>The Chach Nama describes the Ror rulers of Sindh before the Arab conquest. Whether the Rors of modern Haryana directly descend from this dynasty, or merely share a name, cannot be established with current evidence. The connection is plausible but unproven.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Timeline of Key Historical Moments</h3>
      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">~2nd century BCE – 7th century CE</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Ror Dynasty of Sindh</div>
          <div class="timeline-text">The Ror dynasty rules much of Sindh and lower Punjab. References in Chach Nama, Arab chronicles, and regional genealogies. This is the most concrete historical anchor for the Ror name. <span class="epistemic-badge badge-verified">Verified</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">711–713 CE</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Arab Conquest of Sindh</div>
          <div class="timeline-text">Muhammad bin Qasim defeats the last Ror ruler Dahir. The ruling lineage disperses. Oral traditions hold that some Ror clans migrated north toward Punjab and Haryana. <span class="epistemic-badge badge-tradition">Oral Tradition</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">~10th–16th century CE</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Settlement in Haryana Region</div>
          <div class="timeline-text">The Rors become established as an agricultural community in the Kurukshetra-Rohtak belt. Little direct documentary evidence survives from this period. <span class="epistemic-badge badge-hypothesis">Hypothesis</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">1881–1911 CE</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">British Colonial Census</div>
          <div class="timeline-text">Denzil Ibbetson and H.A. Rose document the Rors in their Punjab/North India ethnographic surveys. They are classified as a distinct caste/tribe with agricultural and martial characteristics. <span class="epistemic-badge badge-colonial">Colonial Account</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline-item">
          <div class="timeline-date">2000s–Present</div>
          <div class="timeline-title">Genetic Studies</div>
          <div class="timeline-text">Population genetics research begins including North Indian agrarian castes. The Rors are included in some studies, showing patterns common to North Indian upper-caste populations. <span class="epistemic-badge badge-verified">Verified</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Local North Indian Continuity Theory</h3>
      <p>Against migration narratives, some scholars argue for local origin — that the Rors represent indigenous agrarian communities who have been in the Haryana-Punjab plains for millennia, slowly crystallizing into a distinct jati through endogamy, occupational specialization, and social differentiation.</p>
      <p>This theory aligns better with genetic evidence showing them to be part of the broader North Indian gene pool rather than a distinct migrant group.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-warning" style="margin-top: 40px;">
    <div class="callout-title">Internet Myths vs. Historical Evidence</div>
    <p>Online sources frequently claim Rors are direct descendants of Alexander the Great's soldiers, the Huns, or the Scythians with near-certainty. These claims are not supported by peer-reviewed evidence. Colonial-era ethnographers made speculative suggestions about "foreign" origins for many North Indian castes — modern genetics and anthropology have consistently shown these communities to be part of the indigenous South Asian and Ancestral North Indian (ANI) gene pool, not recent arrivals from Central Asia or the Mediterranean.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ VARNA & DHARMA ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="varna" class="bg-alt" style="max-width:100%; padding: 100px 0;">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Section III</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Hindu Dharma, <em>Varna</em> &amp; Social Identity</h2>
    <p class="section-intro">
      Understanding the Ror community's place in Hindu social structure requires carefully distinguishing between Varna (the four-fold cosmological order), Jati (the lived caste identity), and the community's own claims and traditions.
    </p>

    <h3>The Varna System Explained</h3>
    <div class="varna-tree">
      <div class="varna-node highlight">
        <div class="varna-name">Brahmin</div>
        <div class="varna-desc">Priests &amp; scholars</div>
      </div>
      <div class="varna-node highlight" style="border-color: rgba(212,115,10,0.5); background: rgba(212,115,10,0.14);">
        <div class="varna-name" style="color: var(--saffron-300);">Kshatriya</div>
        <div class="varna-desc">Warriors &amp; rulers</div>
        <div class="varna-ror-claim">← Ror community claim</div>
      </div>
      <div class="varna-node highlight">
        <div class="varna-name">Vaishya</div>
        <div class="varna-desc">Merchants &amp; farmers</div>
      </div>
      <div class="varna-node highlight">
        <div class="varna-name">Shudra</div>
        <div class="varna-desc">Service communities</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout callout-note">
      <div class="callout-title">Critical Distinction: Varna vs. Jati</div>
      <p><strong>Varna</strong> is a theoretical, cosmological framework described in Vedic texts — four broad categories of social function. <strong>Jati</strong> is the lived reality of hundreds of endogamous communities that constitute actual social identity in India. Most jatis, including the Rors, are not directly mentioned in Vedic or Dharmashastra texts. Their Varna claims are assertions of social status, often made during periods of political ambition or social competition — a process scholars call "Sanskritization."</p>
    </div>

    <div class="two-col" style="margin-top: 40px;">
      <div>
        <h3>Are Rors Directly Mentioned in Ancient Hindu Texts?</h3>

        <div class="callout callout-warning">
          <div class="callout-title">Direct Textual Evidence: Absent</div>
          <p>The Rors as a named community are <strong>not mentioned</strong> in the Rigveda, Mahabharata, Ramayana, Manusmriti, or other core Dharmashastra texts by that name. This is the honest scholarly position and should be stated plainly.</p>
        </div>

        <p>What does exist is later — genealogical traditions (vamshavallis) compiled by Brahmin genealogists (Bards, known as Bhats or Jagas) on behalf of landed communities. These genealogies, created in medieval and early modern periods, often trace Ror ancestry to Kshatriya lineages, sometimes linking them to the solar dynasty (Suryavanshi) or connecting them to heroes of the Mahabharata era.</p>
        <p>These genealogies served social and political purposes — legitimating land rights, asserting high status, and establishing alliance networks. They are not historical documents in the modern sense, but they are not fabrications either; they encode collective memory, status negotiations, and regional history in traditional idiom.</p>

        <h3>Ror Claims to Kshatriya Status</h3>
        <p>The Ror community broadly self-identifies as Kshatriya — specifically often asserting descent from the Chandravanshi (lunar dynasty) line, or sometimes Suryavanshi, depending on the region and gotra. Some clans claim descent from the last Ror king Dahir of Sindh.</p>
        <p>This claim aligns structurally with how many North Indian agricultural communities assert Kshatriya identity — through martial history, land ownership, and refusal to accept a subordinate social position. In the colonial-era occupational hierarchies, such claims were intensely contested.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>How Historians Assess These Claims</h3>
        <p>Scholars of South Asian social history note that Kshatriya status for many North Indian communities is often a <em>status claim</em> rather than a documentable <em>historical fact</em>. This is not unique to Rors — Jats, Gujjars, Ahirs, and even some Khatris have made similar claims at various points.</p>
        <p>The relevant question is not "are their Kshatriya claims 'real'?" but rather: <em>how did these communities function in their regional social order?</em> By most indicators — land ownership, warrior roles in medieval armies, refusal of service occupations, marriage patterns — the Rors functioned as a high-status peasant proprietor community, analogous to Jats and Ahirs in their social ecology.</p>

        <div class="pull-quote">
          <p>"Many North Indian cultivating castes claimed Rajput or Kshatriya descent as a matter of social strategy. The claim was part of the politics of status, not necessarily a genealogical record."</p>
          <cite>Paraphrase of Ibbetson, Punjab Castes, 1916 — Colonial Account, treat critically</cite>
        </div>

        <h3>Relationship with Rajputs, Jats &amp; Khatris</h3>
        <p>The Rors occupy an ambiguous social position relative to neighboring communities. They are socially proximate to Jats (shared gotras, similar agrarian identity) but maintain a separate identity. Their relationship with Rajputs is more complex — some Ror traditions claim Rajput origin, while Rajput communities have not historically incorporated Rors into their kinship networks.</p>
        <p>Khatris and Aroras are urban trading communities that share some gotra names with Rors but belong to a functionally different social category. The overlap is likely due to common Punjabi-Haryanvi ancestry rather than direct kinship.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ GENETICS ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="genetics">
  <div class="section-label">Section IV</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Genetics &amp; <em>Population Research</em></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">
    Modern population genetics offers a new lens for understanding community histories — but it is frequently misunderstood and misapplied. Here we present what the science actually shows, and what it does not.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout-warning">
    <div class="callout-title">Critical Caveat: Genetics ≠ Race, Caste, or Identity</div>
    <p>Population genetics identifies statistical patterns in gene frequencies among groups. It does NOT establish racial hierarchies, validate or invalidate social status claims, prove or disprove cultural narratives, or establish that any group is "purer" or "more indigenous" than another. Any claim that genetics "proves" a community's superiority, foreign origin, or ancient purity should be treated with extreme skepticism.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="two-col" style="margin-top: 48px;">
    <div>
      <h3>The ANI / ASI Framework</h3>
      <p>The landmark 2009 study by Reich et al. (Nature) established that most South Asians can be modeled as a mixture of two ancestral populations: Ancestral North Indians (ANI), related to West Eurasians and Central Asians, and Ancestral South Indians (ASI), a deeply indigenous South Asian lineage. Upper-caste North Indian communities typically show higher ANI ancestry; southern and tribal populations typically show higher ASI ancestry.</p>
      <p>The Rors, as a North Indian agrarian community, would be expected to fall within the range of other North Indian upper-caste or peasant proprietor populations — that is, with moderate-to-high ANI admixture, broadly similar to Jats, Khatris, and high-caste Brahmins of Haryana and Punjab.</p>

      <h3>Haplogroup Evidence</h3>
      <p>Y-chromosome haplogroups track patrilineal descent and are the most commonly cited genetic markers in discussions of South Asian caste origins. The following represents the approximate distribution expected and partially documented in North Indian communities like the Rors. Note that community-specific genome-wide data for Rors is limited in the published literature.</p>

      <div class="genetics-section">
        <div class="haplogroup-item">
          <div class="haplogroup-label">
            <span class="haplogroup-name">R1a (especially R1a-Z93)</span>
            <span class="haplogroup-pct">~30–45% est.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-bar-bg">
            <div class="haplogroup-bar" style="width: 40%; background: linear-gradient(to right, var(--saffron-600), var(--saffron-400));"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-desc">The dominant haplogroup in upper-caste North Indian males. Associated with the steppe Yamnaya migration into South Asia (~2000–1500 BCE), which brought Indo-Aryan languages. High frequency among Brahmins, Rajputs, and Jats of North India. This is likely significant among Rors.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="haplogroup-item">
          <div class="haplogroup-label">
            <span class="haplogroup-name">J2</span>
            <span class="haplogroup-pct">~10–20% est.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-bar-bg">
            <div class="haplogroup-bar" style="width: 15%; background: linear-gradient(to right, var(--accent-teal), #4a9e9e);"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-desc">Common across West Asia, the Indian Subcontinent, and Mediterranean populations. Associated with Neolithic farmers and possibly with some early urban (Harappan-adjacent) populations.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="haplogroup-item">
          <div class="haplogroup-label">
            <span class="haplogroup-name">L (L-M20)</span>
            <span class="haplogroup-pct">~8–15% est.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-bar-bg">
            <div class="haplogroup-bar" style="width: 12%; background: linear-gradient(to right, var(--bronze-600), var(--bronze-500));"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-desc">An ancient South Asian lineage, very common among Pakistani and Northwestern Indian populations. Often associated with Indus Valley Civilization populations and their descendants. Presence signals deep indigenous South Asian ancestry.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="haplogroup-item">
          <div class="haplogroup-label">
            <span class="haplogroup-name">H (H-M69)</span>
            <span class="haplogroup-pct">~5–12% est.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-bar-bg">
            <div class="haplogroup-bar" style="width: 8%; background: linear-gradient(to right, var(--stone-600), var(--stone-500));"></div>
          </div>
          <div class="haplogroup-desc">Deep indigenous South Asian lineage. More common among service castes and some tribal groups in northern India. Lower frequency expected among Rors but may be present.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-note">
        <div class="callout-title">Data Limitation</div>
        <p>Genome-wide published data specifically labeled "Ror" is sparse in the literature. Most estimates here draw from patterns observed in genetically proximate communities (Jats, Haryanvi Brahmins, Northwestern Indian populations). Community-specific comprehensive studies are needed before firm conclusions can be drawn.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Steppe Ancestry &amp; What It Means</h3>
      <p>Recent archaeogenetic studies (Narasimhan et al., Science, 2019; Lazaridis et al., 2022) have documented a significant migration of Steppe pastoralists (Yamnaya-related) into South Asia during the Bronze Age, approximately 2000–1500 BCE. This migration is now linked to the spread of Indo-Aryan languages and the Vedic culture into the subcontinent.</p>
      <p>Upper-caste North Indians carry more of this steppe-related ancestry than lower-caste populations — a pattern consistent with the social stratification that accompanied or followed this migration. Rors, as a North Indian agrarian community with Kshatriya claims, likely carry steppe ancestry in a range similar to Jats and upper-caste Haryanvi populations.</p>
      <p>This does NOT mean Rors are "descended from Aryans" in a racial sense, or that any group with steppe ancestry is "superior." It means their ancestral population participated in the demographic and cultural processes that shaped North Indian civilization over several millennia.</p>

      <h3>Are the Rors "Foreign" to India?</h3>
      <p>Definitively: <strong>no more than any other North Indian community.</strong> All South Asian populations represent a complex blend of multiple ancestral streams — the Ancestral South Indians (the oldest layer, present for 50,000+ years), the Iranian-related Neolithic farmers who may have been associated with the Indus Valley Civilization, and the steppe pastoralists who arrived in the Bronze Age.</p>
      <p>The Rors are a product of this same history. Singling out Rors as "Scythian foreigners" — as colonial ethnographers sometimes did — reflects 19th-century racial categorization, not modern anthropological understanding.</p>

      <h3>Genetic Overlap with Neighboring Communities</h3>
      <p>The most important finding from population genetics for understanding the Rors: they likely cluster genetically with Jats, Haryanvi Brahmins, and other North Indian agricultural communities. There is no evidence of a genetically distinct "Ror population" sharply differentiated from their neighbors. This suggests deep shared history and intermixing over millennia — consistent with local origin theories rather than a distinct migration event.</p>

      <h3>Key References</h3>
      <div class="citation-block">
        <div class="citation-title">Relevant Academic Literature</div>
        <p class="citation-item">Reich, D. et al. (2009). "Reconstructing Indian population history." <em>Nature</em>, 461, 489–494. [ANI/ASI framework]</p>
        <p class="citation-item">Narasimhan, V.M. et al. (2019). "The formation of human populations in South and Central Asia." <em>Science</em>, 365(6457). [Steppe ancestry and Bronze Age migrations]</p>
        <p class="citation-item">Basu, A. et al. (2016). "Genomic reconstruction of the history of extant populations of India reveals five distinct ancestral components." <em>PNAS</em>, 113(6). [Five-component South Asian ancestry model]</p>
        <p class="citation-item">Thangaraj, K. et al. Various papers on South Asian Y-chromosome diversity. [Haplogroup distributions]</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ HISTORIOGRAPHY ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="historiography" class="bg-dark" style="max-width:100%; padding: 100px 0;">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Section V</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Historiography &amp; <em>Colonial Accounts</em></h2>
    <p class="section-intro">
      The major written records about the Rors come primarily from the British colonial era. Understanding these sources requires understanding the agendas and limitations of their authors.
    </p>

    <div class="card-grid">
      <div class="card">
        <h4>Colonial Account</h4>
        <h3>Denzil Ibbetson</h3>
        <p>In <em>Punjab Castes</em> (1916, based on 1881 census data), Ibbetson provides one of the earliest systematic accounts of the Rors. He classifies them as a distinct caste/tribe of Haryana, notes their agricultural character, their Kshatriya claims, and their spatial relationship to Jats. His framework was shaped by a racial-administrative logic that sought to "fix" fluid communities into permanent categories — a significant limitation when reading his work today.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h4>Colonial Account</h4>
        <h3>H.A. Rose</h3>
        <p>Rose's <em>A Glossary of the Tribes and Castes of the Punjab and North-West Frontier Province</em> (1911–1919) provides additional documentary detail on Ror customs, gotras, and regional distribution. Rose largely follows Ibbetson's framework. His work is valuable as historical documentation but must be read critically — colonial ethnographers often had limited access, relied on informants with their own agendas, and projected Western racial categories onto South Asian social reality.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h4>Colonial Account</h4>
        <h3>Herbert Hope Risley</h3>
        <p>Risley's anthropometric approach to caste (measuring skull dimensions as proxies for racial origin) is now scientifically discredited. However, his census work and <em>The Tribes and Castes of Bengal</em> set a framework that influenced how British administrators classified all North Indian communities, including indirectly shaping how Rors were categorized in relation to "martial races" and caste hierarchy.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h4>Medieval Source</h4>
        <h3>Chach Nama</h3>
        <p>The Arab chronicle of the conquest of Sindh (8th century, translated from Arabic, possibly based on an earlier Persian version) is the primary historical document mentioning the Ror dynasty by name. It describes Dahir, the last Ror king, and his defeat by Muhammad bin Qasim in 711–713 CE. While the text has its own political agenda, it represents the most concrete pre-colonial reference to the Ror name. Scholars including Manan Ahmed Asif have analyzed its layers critically.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h4>Modern Scholarship</h4>
        <h3>Regional Gazetteers &amp; District Records</h3>
        <p>Post-independence India's district gazetteers (Rohtak, Sonipat, Hisar, Karnal) contain references to the Ror community in local context — land ownership records, panchayat histories, and community participation in agriculture and local governance. These are underexplored sources for understanding Ror history on the ground, outside the colonial gaze.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h4>Critical Approach</h4>
        <h3>Post-Colonial Reassessment</h3>
        <p>Since the 1990s, scholars including Nicholas Dirks (<em>Castes of Mind</em>, 2001) have argued that colonial enumeration and categorization substantially transformed Indian caste identity — turning fluid, context-dependent identities into fixed, enumerated categories. The Rors' distinct identity as a caste was, in part, crystallized and rigidified by the colonial census apparatus. This does not mean the community is an invention — but their sharp distinctiveness from Jats may be partly a colonial artifact.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

