<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ SOCIAL & CULTURAL IDENTITY ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="culture" class="bg-alt" style="max-width:100%; padding: 100px 0;">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Section VII</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Social &amp; <em>Cultural Identity</em></h2>
    <p class="section-intro">
      Beyond historical claims and genetic patterns, the Rors are a living community with specific cultural practices, traditions, and a modern identity shaped by 20th-century social change.
    </p>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div>
        <h3>Marriage Customs</h3>
        <p>Ror marriage is strictly endogamous at the community level — Rors traditionally marry other Rors. Within this, gotra exogamy applies: marriage within the same gotra (patrilineal clan) is prohibited. Some additional prohibitions apply to the mother's and grandmother's clans. Arranged marriages predominate, though this is changing among urban-educated Rors.</p>
        <p>This high degree of endogamy over many generations has had a genetic consequence: the Ror population likely shows founder effects and limited heterozygosity relative to larger neighboring communities. This is consistent with what population genetics predicts for small, isolated populations.</p>

        <h3>Religious Traditions</h3>
        <p>The Rors are Hindu, primarily worshipping the mainstream Shaiva and Vaishnava traditions of North India. Ancestor worship and village deity (<em>Kul Devta/Devī</em>) traditions are important. Like most Haryanvi communities, they celebrate major Hindu festivals — Holi, Diwali, Teej, and Navratri — with local cultural inflections.</p>
        <p>Some gotras have specific patron deities or clan traditions that distinguish them within the broader Ror community. Pilgrimages to sites in Kurukshetra hold particular significance given the region's Mahabharata associations.</p>

        <h3>Language &amp; Dialect</h3>
        <p>Haryanvi (a dialect of Western Hindi, classified by some linguists as part of the Khariboli continuum) is the primary spoken language. Standard Hindi is used for formal and educational purposes. With urbanization, Hindi and English are becoming dominant among younger Rors in Delhi, Chandigarh, and other cities.</p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3>Agricultural Identity</h3>
        <p>Wheat and sugarcane cultivation are the primary agricultural activities in the Ror heartland. The community's identity is deeply tied to land ownership — having land confers status, while landlessness historically implied social decline. The Green Revolution of the 1960s–70s transformed Haryana's agricultural economy, and Ror farmers participated in this transformation, though the community's small population means they did not achieve the collective political weight that Jats did.</p>

        <h3>Modern Socioeconomic Position</h3>
        <p>Like many North Indian agricultural castes, Rors face the challenges of agricultural fragmentation (land divided among generations), rural-urban migration, and competition in modern economies. The community does not have a formal Other Backward Classes (OBC) or Scheduled Caste reservation status in most states, meaning they compete in the general category for education and government employment.</p>
        <p>There are no widely known Ror political figures of national prominence, reflecting the community's small size and limited collective political organization. Some Rors have served in the Indian Army, consistent with the region's military traditions.</p>

        <h3>Rare Facts &amp; Lesser-Known Dimensions</h3>
        <div class="card-grid" style="margin-top: 16px; grid-template-columns: 1fr;">
          <div class="card" style="margin-top: 0;">
            <h4>Founder Effect</h4>
            <h3>The Genetics of Small Population Endogamy</h3>
            <p>The Rors' small population size combined with strict endogamy over centuries almost certainly means they display stronger founder effects than Jats or Rajputs. This is a scientifically interesting case study in how endogamy shapes population genetics — but it says nothing about genetic "superiority" or "purity."</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card" style="margin-top: 0;">
            <h4>Historical Curiosity</h4>
            <h3>Shared Gotras, Disputed Kinship</h3>
            <p>The fact that Rors share gotras like Dahiya, Sangwan, and Phogat with Jats — communities that don't intermarry and claim separate origins — raises a genuine historical puzzle. The most parsimonious explanation is common ancestry with differentiation through endogamy, rather than separate origins that happened to develop identical gotra names.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ MISUNDERSTOOD CLAIMS ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="myths">
  <div class="section-label">Section VIII</div>
  <h2 class="section-title">Most <em>Misunderstood Claims</em></h2>
  <p class="section-intro">
    Online discussions of the Ror community are often polluted by unverifiable claims, nationalist mythology, and colonial-era pseudo-science repackaged as fact. We address the most common here.
  </p>

  <div class="card-grid">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Myth</h4>
      <h3>"Rors are descended from Alexander the Great's army"</h3>
      <p>This claim has no credible historical or genetic support. It is a variant of a colonial-era trope applied to multiple North Indian communities. Alexander's campaign reached northwestern India (326 BCE), and while some soldiers may have remained, their genetic contribution to any specific modern community is negligible and untrackable.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Myth</h4>
      <h3>"Rors are Scythian/Saka by origin"</h3>
      <p>Colonial ethnographers speculated this for many North Indian castes. Modern geneticists and historians do not support blanket "Scythian" identifications. Saka was a political/administrative category. Even if Saka groups settled in Northwest India (which they did), their contribution to any modern community's gene pool would be mixed with existing South Asian populations over 2,000 years.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Overstated</h4>
      <h3>"Rors are the original Kshatriyas / most ancient Hindus"</h3>
      <p>Claims of being the "most ancient" or "purest" community are not scientifically meaningful. All South Asian communities share ancient ancestry. The Rors have no demonstrated priority over Jats, Rajputs, or neighboring communities in terms of antiquity of settlement in Haryana. Such claims reflect community pride but not historical scholarship.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Uncertain</h4>
      <h3>"Modern Rors directly descend from the Sindhi Ror dynasty"</h3>
      <p>This is the most plausible of the major claims, but remains unproven. The geographic and temporal gap (Sindh, 7th–8th century CE → Haryana plains, ongoing) is not impossible but is not documented. It's a reasonable hypothesis, not an established fact.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Contested</h4>
      <h3>"Rors are entirely distinct from Jats"</h3>
      <p>The gotra overlap and genetic proximity to Jat populations suggests shared ancestry. The distinctiveness of Rors as a community is real — they maintain a separate social identity — but this distinctiveness is likely a product of endogamy-driven differentiation from a common ancestral population, not separate origins.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Colonial Error</h4>
      <h3>"Ror genetic makeup proves foreign origin"</h3>
      <p>High R1a frequency does not prove "foreign" origin. R1a has been in South Asia for at least 4,000 years. Every North Indian upper-caste community shows elevated R1a. There is nothing genetically "foreign" about Rors relative to their North Indian neighbors.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ FAQ ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="faq" class="bg-dark" style="max-width:100%; padding: 100px 0;">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Section IX</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked <em>Questions</em></h2>
    <p class="section-intro">
      Honest answers to the most common questions about the Ror community, distinguishing evidence from tradition.
    </p>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
        <span class="accordion-q">Are the Rors mentioned in the Vedas or Mahabharata?</span>
        <span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-content">
        <p>No — not by that name. The Rors as a named jati do not appear in Vedic texts, the Mahabharata, Ramayana, or core Dharmashastra literature. This is not unusual — almost no modern jati is directly named in ancient Sanskrit literature. What exists are later genealogical traditions (compiled by Brahmin bards) that retrospectively connect Ror lineages to Vedic or Kshatriya ancestry. These traditions are culturally important but should not be confused with ancient historical documentation.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
        <span class="accordion-q">Are Rors Kshatriya?</span>
        <span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-content">
        <p>The Rors self-identify as Kshatriya, and this claim has functional validity in the sense that they historically performed warrior and land-owner roles associated with Kshatriya function. However, Varna identity for agrarian communities in North India is a complex sociohistorical matter. No ancient Sanskrit text directly classifies Rors as Kshatriya. Their claim is one of social assertion — shared with Jats, Gujjars, and many other communities — rather than documented ancient genealogy. Scholars generally treat such claims as historically meaningful social facts, not literal genealogical truths.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
        <span class="accordion-q">Are Rors and Jats the same community?</span>
        <span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-content">
        <p>No — they are distinct communities that do not intermarry. However, they share significant gotra names (Dahiya, Sangwan, Phogat, Mor, and others) and occupy structurally similar social niches. The most historically parsimonious explanation is that both communities share common ancestry from the broader North Indian agrarian-martial population of Haryana and Punjab, with differentiation occurring through endogamy over many centuries. The Rors are much smaller, geographically more concentrated, and lack the Jats' political and military prominence.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
        <span class="accordion-q">What does genetics actually tell us about the Rors?</span>
        <span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-content">
        <p>Published genome-wide studies specifically labeled "Ror" are limited. Based on their position as a North Indian upper-caste agricultural community, we can expect them to show: (1) moderate-to-high Ancestral North Indian (ANI) admixture; (2) elevated R1a-Z93 haplogroup frequency, associated with Bronze Age steppe migrations that brought Indo-Aryan languages to South Asia; (3) genetic clustering with neighboring communities like Jats and Haryanvi Brahmins. This does NOT make them "foreign" — this is the ancestral profile common to most upper-caste North Indians. A comprehensive, community-specific genetic study of Rors would be scientifically valuable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
        <span class="accordion-q">Is there a historical connection to the Ror kingdom of Sindh?</span>
        <span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-content">
        <p>The Ror dynasty of Sindh is historically real — documented in the Chach Nama and Arab chronicles, ruling until the Arab conquest of 711–713 CE. The connection between this dynasty and the modern Ror community of Haryana is plausible but not proven. Geographic migration from Sindh northward following the Arab conquest is a reasonable hypothesis. The shared name is the strongest evidence. However, no direct genealogical documentation links the two, and the 1,300-year gap means considerable mixing with other North Indian populations would have occurred regardless.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
        <span class="accordion-q">Why are Rors such a small community?</span>
        <span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-content">
        <p>Strict endogamy is the primary explanation. A community that has maintained very rigid in-group marriage for centuries does not absorb outside members or expand through conversion. It can only grow through natural increase within the community. This distinguishes Rors from Jats, who were a much larger community and may have historically incorporated other agrarian groups. The Rors' small size is consistent with a founder-effect scenario — a relatively small original group that has remained reproductively isolated for an extended period.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="accordion-item">
      <button class="accordion-trigger" onclick="toggleAccordion(this)">
        <span class="accordion-q">Do the Rors have OBC or reservation status?</span>
        <span class="accordion-icon">+</span>
      </button>
      <div class="accordion-content">
        <p>As of the most recent available information, the Rors are generally classified in the general (unreserved) category and do not hold OBC status in Haryana or most other states. They are not classified as Scheduled Castes (SC) or Scheduled Tribes (ST). Their relative social position — as a landed, Kshatriya-claiming agricultural community — has historically placed them in the general category. This means they compete without reservation benefits in education and government employment, which has implications for their economic mobility given their small population size and lack of large-city economic networks.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<div class="section-divider"></div>

<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ ACADEMIC SUMMARY ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="summary">
  <div class="section-label">Final Summary</div>
  <h2 class="section-title"><em>Academic</em> Consensus &amp; Open Questions</h2>
  <p class="section-intro">
    A balanced synthesis of what scholarship actually tells us — and where genuine uncertainty remains.
  </p>

  <div class="two-col-wide">
    <div>
      <h3>What We Can Say with Confidence</h3>
      <p><strong>The Rors are a real, historically documented community</strong> of North India with a continuous presence in the Haryana region, documented at least from the colonial-era census records and plausibly traceable to early medieval period through the Sindh connection.</p>
      <p><strong>Their social identity is agrarian-martial,</strong> placing them alongside Jats, Gujjars, and Rajputs as landed peasant proprietors who claim Kshatriya status and historically provided military service in regional armies.</p>
      <p><strong>Genetically, they are part of the North Indian gene pool,</strong> sharing ancestry with neighboring communities and carrying the mix of steppe-related, Iranian-Neolithic, and indigenous South Asian ancestries that characterizes most upper-caste North Indians.</p>
      <p><strong>No ancient Sanskrit text mentions them by name.</strong> Their Kshatriya status is a social claim with historical functional validity, not a documented ancient genealogy.</p>
      <p><strong>The Ror dynasty of Sindh connection is the strongest historical claim</strong> and merits further scholarly investigation, but cannot be considered proven with current evidence.</p>

      <h3>Major Open Questions</h3>
      <p>1. A comprehensive genome-wide study of the Ror population would be scientifically valuable and is currently lacking in the published literature.</p>
      <p>2. Medieval documentation of Rors in Haryana prior to the colonial period is sparse. Regional historical archaeology and medieval Persian/Sanskrit sources from the Kurukshetra-Rohtak area may contain relevant material not yet synthesized.</p>
      <p>3. The precise relationship between the Sindhi Ror dynasty and the modern Haryanvi Ror community deserves dedicated genealogical and historical research, free from both colonial bias and nationalist inflation.</p>
      <p>4. The mechanism of Ror differentiation from the Jat community — whether through migration, political differentiation, or gradual endogamic isolation — remains unclear.</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Colonial vs. Modern Framework</h3>
      <div class="reading-list">
        <div class="reading-item">
          <span class="reading-tag">Colonial</span>
          <div class="reading-content">
            <strong>Racial origin theories</strong>
            <span>Scythian, Macedonian, or "foreign" descent narratives — now rejected by mainstream anthropology</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reading-item">
          <span class="reading-tag">Colonial</span>
          <div class="reading-content">
            <strong>Fixed caste categories</strong>
            <span>Census-created rigidity that overstated distinctiveness between communities</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reading-item">
          <span class="reading-tag">Modern</span>
          <div class="reading-content">
            <strong>Mixed ancestry model</strong>
            <span>All South Asians are products of multiple ancient migrations; no community is "purely" anything</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reading-item">
          <span class="reading-tag">Modern</span>
          <div class="reading-content">
            <strong>Social construction of caste</strong>
            <span>Caste identities are real but historically contingent — shaped by politics, endogamy, and state power</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Recommended Reading</h3>
      <div class="reading-list">
        <div class="reading-item">
          <span class="reading-tag">History</span>
          <div class="reading-content">
            <strong>Denzil Ibbetson — Punjab Castes (1916)</strong>
            <span>Colonial primary source; read critically for historical documentation</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="reading-item">
          <span class="reading-tag">History</span>
          <div class="reading-content">
            <strong>Manan Ahmed Asif — A Book of Conquest (2016)</strong>
            <span>Critical reading of the Chach Nama; essential for Sindh/Ror history</span>
          </div>
        </div>
