<!-- ═══════════════════════════════ GLOSSARY ═══════════════════════════════ -->
<section id="glossary" class="bg-alt" style="max-width:100%; padding: 80px 0;">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="section-label">Reference</div>
    <h2 class="section-title">Glossary of <em>Key Terms</em></h2>

    <div class="glossary-grid">
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Varna</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">The four-fold cosmological-social division in Hindu tradition: Brahmin, Kshatriya, Vaishya, Shudra. A theoretical framework; most modern jatis don't map cleanly onto it.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Jati</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">The actual lived community — endogamous, hereditary, occupation-associated. Hundreds of jatis exist across India. The Ror is a jati, not a Varna.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Gotra</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">Patrilineal clan within a jati, tracing descent from a common ancestor (often a Vedic sage). Marriage within the same gotra is traditionally forbidden.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Endogamy</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">The practice of marrying within a defined community. Strict endogamy over generations causes genetic drift and founder effects, making communities genetically distinct from their neighbors.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">ANI / ASI</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">Ancestral North Indians and Ancestral South Indians — the two major ancestral components of South Asian populations identified by Reich et al. (2009). Not racial categories; statistical ancestry components.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Haplogroup</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">A genetic lineage tracked through Y-chromosome (paternal) or mitochondrial DNA (maternal) — a group of people sharing a common ancestor. R1a, J2, L, and H are major haplogroups relevant to South Asian studies.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Steppe Ancestry</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">Genetic ancestry related to the Yamnaya / Pontic-Caspian steppe pastoralists who migrated into South Asia ~2000–1500 BCE, associated with the spread of Indo-Aryan languages and Vedic culture.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Sanskritization</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">Sociologist M.N. Srinivas's term for the process by which lower-caste or tribal communities adopt upper-caste practices, rituals, and claims to raise their social status.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Founder Effect</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">When a population is established by a small number of ancestors, limiting genetic diversity. Strict endogamy amplifies this over generations.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Chach Nama</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">An Arab chronicle of the conquest of Sindh (711–713 CE), originally in Arabic, later translated to Persian. Primary historical source mentioning the Ror dynasty of Sindh.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Archaeogenetics</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">The study of ancient DNA extracted from archaeological remains to understand prehistoric population movements. Has transformed understanding of South Asian population history since ~2015.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Jajmani System</div>
        <div class="glossary-def">The traditional North Indian system of hereditary exchange relationships between service castes and patron castes in a village. Agrarian communities like Rors occupied the patron role.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
